STREPTOCOCCUS, GROUP A - UK: (ENGLAND) INVASIVE, CHILDREN, FATAL
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Fri 25 Nov 2022
Source: Surrey News [abridged, edited]
https://news.surreycc.gov.uk/2022/11/25/cases-of-invasive-group-a-streptococcal-igas-infection-at-a-surrey-school/


Specialists from the United Kingdom Health Security Agency (UKHSA) have arranged for antibiotics to be offered to pupils and staff in year 1 and 2 [aged 5-7 years] at a Surrey school as a precautionary measure, following 2 cases of invasive group A streptococcal infection (iGAS) [also known as _Streptococcus pyogenes_]. Sadly, one pupil from Ashford Church of England Primary School has died, and another is in hospital but showing positive signs of recovery.

Dr Claire Winslade, health protection consultant at UKHSA South East, said: "As a precautionary measure, we have recommended antibiotics to pupils and staff in years 1 and 2, the same year groups as the individuals affected. We have provided advice to the school to help prevent further cases and will continue to monitor the situation. Information has been shared with parents about the signs and symptoms of iGAS [invasive group A streptococcal infection], which include high fever with severe muscle aches, pain in one area of the body and unexplained vomiting or diarrhoea. Anyone with these symptoms should call NHS111 immediately."

Infection with group A streptococcus bacteria usually causes a sore throat or skin rash and is passed by physical contact or through droplets from sneezing or coughing. In very rare cases, the infection can become invasive and enter parts of the body where bacteria aren't normally found, which can be serious.

A number of other illnesses typically circulate at this time of year, and parents, school and nursery staff are advised to be aware of the symptoms. Dr Winslade added: "We are also seeing cases of scarlet fever [a GAS] infection, RSV and other viral infections in the community, which are all fairly common among children. Please ensure that children stay off school if they're unwell to help minimise the spread of infections and check that they are up to date with their routine vaccinations. Always contact your GP for medical advice if you are concerned."

Because group A streptococcal disease is spread through coughing, sneezing and skin contact, it's important to have good hand hygiene and catch coughs and sneezes in tissues and throw these away. If you are unwell, stay at home and seek medical advice. This will all help limit the spread of other infections, which are common this time of year.

