communicated by:
ProMED

[Ashford Church of England Primary School is in Surrey, a county in the south east of England, bordering Greater London (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surrey). A map showing the location of the Ashford school can be found at https://tinyurl.com/594zr8hn.

Over a century ago, scarlet fever was feared as a potentially lethal disease caused group A streptococcus (GAS, also known as _Streptococcus pyogenes_). Scarlet fever's mortality and morbidity waned, however, well before antibiotics became available. Since the advent of antibiotic therapy, the mortality rate of treated scarlet fever has been less than one percent. Community-wide outbreaks still occur, as has happened in the UK. However, in contrast to scarlet fever, which is a noninvasive form of GAS infection, invasive GAS infections (including bacteremia, necrotizing fasciitis, toxic shock syndrome, endocarditis, puerperal sepsis, pneumonia, and meningitis) are severe and often life-threatening.

ProMED has posted multiple reports since 2013 on large outbreaks of scarlet fever throughout England and Wales (see the See Also section below). Subsequently, ProMED posted reports of outbreaks of invasive GAS infection (necrotizing fasciitis) in 2019 in England (ProMED posts Streptococcus, group A, invasive - UK (02): (England) fatal, WGS 20190807.6611267 and Streptococcus, group A, invasive - UK: (England) fatal, RFI 20190628.6542184).

Scarlet fever is usually associated with concurrent streptococcal pharyngitis, but may be associated with a streptococcal infection at other sites. The distinctive skin rash and red tongue characteristic of scarlet fever is caused by an exotoxin released by strains of _S. pyogenes_. Complications of scarlet fever include local spread of the streptococcal throat infection to involve regional lymph nodes, retropharyngeal tissues, middle ear, and sinuses, and immune-mediated diseases such as acute rheumatic fever (ARF) and post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. However, septic complications of scarlet fever due to spread of GAS in bloodstream, such as meningitis, pyogenic arthritis, and endocarditis, rarely occur.

The incidence of GAS pharyngeal disease is highest in school-aged children (5-15 years), during winter and spring, and in a setting of crowding and close contact. Person-to-person spread from infected patients by means of respiratory droplets is the most common mode of transmission. It can rarely be spread through contaminated food (http://www.nejm.org/doi/pdf/10.1056/NEJM196904242801702).

The M surface protein is the major somatic virulence factor of GAS, which have been divided into serotypes based on the antigenic differences in the M protein molecule. More recently, GAS are typed on the basis of sequence analysis of the portion of the emm gene that encodes M serospecificity (https://www.cdc.gov/streplab/groupa-strep/emm-background.html).

The news report does not specify the M (emm) protein type that is involved in the current outbreak in Surrey, UK; however, upper respiratory GAS isolates having a distinctive emm type 1 (designated M1UK) increased significantly in England over the time period of 2014 to 2016, so that by 2016 it represented 84% of all emm1 strains isolated (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6838661/). The new strain's emergence coincided with a rise invasive GAS infections in the UK. The invasive GAS isolates collected in the same period in the UK were also M1UK (https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(19)30446-3/fulltext). M1UK was found to produce 9 times more streptococcal exotoxin than previous version of emm type 1 isolates.

More information on this outbreak in Surrey would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources as it becomes available. - Mod.ML

